# PBX Architecture

Before implementing or modifying any PBX / telephony feature:

## Mandatory understanding

1. Read relevant docs in `docs/vsp/pbx/` and `docs/vsp/architecture-decisions/`
2. Check feature status in `docs/vsp/features.md`
3. Trace existing call flow — do not invent parallel paths
4. Identify which modules own the feature today (`lib/inboundCallControl.js`, `lib/callControlSessionStore.js`, etc.)

## Hard rules

- **Reuse existing architecture** — extend Call Control FSM and Redis sessions
- **Never introduce duplicate call flows** — no second inbound handler, no parallel TeXML+CC logic for new features
- **Never duplicate session management** — use `ccs:*` and `cts:*` keys only via `callControlSessionStore.js` / `callTransferControl.js`
- **Never bypass tenant isolation** — all queries scoped by `tenantId` from JWT or DID resolution
- **Never bypass Call Control** for server-side call orchestration — use `lib/telnyxCallControl.js`
- **Never bypass Redis session management** for ephemeral call state in production

## Protected components

Changes to these require regression analysis (see `protected-telephony-components.mdc`):

- `lib/inboundCallControl.js`, `lib/telnyxCallControl.js`, `lib/callControlSessionStore.js`
- `web/src/lib/webrtc-audio.ts`, `web/src/lib/telnyx-softphone-session.ts`
- `web/src/app/(app)/softphone-v2/page.tsx`

## Before code changes for production issues

Follow `deployment-safety.mdc` — verify deploy state before blaming application logic.

